Notes: The substrate of the area chosen for the tows and the squid-pops trials is muddy, and the intertidal and subtidal zones are dominated by two types of habitat, which we sampled. Areas devoid of vegetation from the channel to the upper intertidal (unvegetated) usually have patches of eelgrass. Tows we did in this area inevitably passed through some of these patches, but these patches represented less than 5% of the total sampled area.
The width and height of the seine net used is 9 meters and 1.5 meters respectively. The mesh openning is 4 mm.
Participant List: Clara M. Hereu; Pablo Jorgensen; Luis R. Robles

Notes: The seagrass habitat sampled was conformed by continuous meadows of eelgrass, which in its deepest part started in a shallow channel of about 1 m at MLLW to about 5-10 cm deep (during the sampling time, low tide) towards the beach. From then until the upper intertidal, covered by salt marsh plants, the area sampled was dominated by a matrix devoid of vegetation. This means that tows made on seagrass invariably swept an area very shallow (<10 cm) without vegetation in the last ~5 meters of trawling (<15% of toal area covered by trawls in the seagrass habitat).
